<WRITING SEX="FEMALE" PERSON="BRWWRITER"><ORLANDOHEADER TYPE="text"><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><DOCTITLE>Naomi Jacob: writing</DOCTITLE></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><AUTHORITY>Orlando Project</AUTHORITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC>Based on original research by members of the Orlando Project.</SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="RSC" WORKSTATUS="SUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>28 June 1999</DATE><ITEM>Initial document given to tagger.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>21 December 1999</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily orgName and bibCit cleanup</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="DRG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>1 February 2001</DATE><ITEM>converted textual apostrophes and quotation marks to entity references</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>6 January 2002</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 April 2003</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily PLACE cleanup</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>16 June 2003</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily TGENRENAME cleanup, BIBCIT following P moved before P, BIBCITS TAG added</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>08 April 2005</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: March 2005 Specifications. Mainly tag/attribute name changes</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>12 July 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>20 July 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>12 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>17 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>29 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>31 August 2011</DATE><ITEM>rwt c, ready for cas</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>4 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>5 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>6 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>7 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>11 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>12 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>13 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 October 2011</DATE><ITEM>Hi! Thanks Isobel for responding to my research notes. It was interesting to learn about the tgenre tag - I didn&apos;t realize there could be two categories for one text. There are two more notes at the end of the document that still need to be checked. All the best,Nadine</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>14 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>26 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>24 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>25 November 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, rbv c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFB" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>7 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>8 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft i</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>12 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, pilot 43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>12 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>13 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>15 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="pub" RESP="MPO" WORKVALUE="c"><DATE>16 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c pilot43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Writing</HEADING><STANDARD>Jacob, Naomi</STANDARD><AUTHORSUMMARY><SHORTPROSE><P><GENERICRANGE><EXTENTOFOEUVRE>NJ was a highly prolific, <TGENRE GENRENAME="POPULAR">popular</TGENRE> author, whose profitable writing career began in the 1920s and produced more than seventy books.</EXTENTOFOEUVRE> The greater number are <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE>, including a notable series detailing for fortunes of an English Jewish family. Her fiction became steadily more formulaic with time. She also wrote <TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">plays</TGENRE>, <TGENRE GENRENAME="JOURNALISM">journalism</TGENRE>, <TGENRE GENRENAME="PROGRAMNOTES">opera program notes</TGENRE>, and whatever came to hand. She issued several volumes of <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">rambling memoirs which include much  entertaining theatre reminiscence</TGENRE> (every one of which has the word <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Me</QUOTE> in its title) and a <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE> of <NAME>Marie Lloyd</NAME>.</GENERICRANGE> She was well-known on the stage in her earlier life, and later on as a broadcaster.</P></SHORTPROSE></AUTHORSUMMARY><DIV1><HEADING>Starting Young</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>When she was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">very young</QUOTE>, NJ wrote a fan <TGENRE GENRENAME="JUVENILIA"><TGENRE GENRENAME="LETTER">letter</TGENRE></TGENRE> to an author, <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO"><NAME>R. B. Cunninghame Graham</NAME>. Her letter moved him to reply: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I believe that one day you will write yourself.</QUOTE> She cherished this answer.</RRESPONSES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 239" DBREF="68825">239</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><DIV2><HEADING>Drama</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104711" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, The Dawn, 1923"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="PERIOD"><DATE VALUE="1923--">1923</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PPERFORMANCE><PFIRSTLITERARYACTIVITY>NJ is said to have had a <TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">play</TGENRE> staged entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">The Dawn</TITLE>. Like her later plays, it seems not to have been reached print.</PFIRSTLITERARYACTIVITY></PPERFORMANCE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>She mentions two <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORICAL">historical</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="ONEACTPLAY">one-acters</TGENRE> which she later wrote, both on Scottish themes. <TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST"><PPERFORMANCE>One, about <NAME STANDARD="Stuart, Charles Edward">Bonnie Prince Charlie</NAME> as a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">tired, disappointed exile</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE></QUOTE> after his attempt on the throne, was staged by the <ORGNAME>Scottish National Players</ORGNAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 215" DBREF="68825">215</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="UPPERCLASS">The other, about the <TTHEMETOPIC>imprisonment of <NAME STANDARD="Mary,, Queen of Scots">Mary Queen of Scots</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> in <PLACE><PLACENAME>Sheffield Castle</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Sheffield"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> under the care of <NAME STANDARD="Shrewsbury, Elizabeth Talbot,,, Countess of">Bess of Hardwick</NAME>,</TSETTINGPLACE> was recommended through a friend of NJ to the <ORGNAME>Masque Players</ORGNAME> of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Edinburgh</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Midlothian"></REGION><GEOG REG="Scotland"></GEOG></PLACE>. It was acted there and in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Glasgow</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Lanarkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="Scotland"></GEOG></PLACE>, with the author playing a small role,</PPERFORMANCE></TSETTINGDATE> and was a success, although NJ and the leading lady, <NAME>Maud Risdon</NAME>, were somewhat incompatible characters. Jacob later <TGENRE GENRENAME="ADAPTATION">adapted</TGENRE> this play into a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mary of Delight</TITLE>, 1949.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 216-17" DBREF="68825">216-17</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 155" DBREF="68930">155</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Catalogue" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><DIV2><HEADING>Novels Between the Wars</HEADING><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ&apos;s concept of character-drawing (according to biographer <NAME>Paul Bailey</NAME>) <TCHARACTERIZATION><TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="NONSTANDARDENGLISH">was heavily reliant on stereotypes of racial or local disposition, shown through idiosyncratic, uneducated use of language.</TTECHNIQUES></TCHARACTERIZATION></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Jacob Ussher</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104706" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Jacob Ussher, 1925"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1925-06-25" CERTAINTY="BY">By late June 1925</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PCIRCULATION>NJ scored a success with her first <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Jacob Ussher</TITLE>, which became a best-seller.</PCIRCULATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1223 (25 June 1925): 427" DBREF="54246">(25 June 1925): 427</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Naomi Jacob" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ADAPTATION-UPDATE" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">It was, she said, an <TGENRE GENRENAME="ADAPTATION">adaptation</TGENRE> from a play by <NAME>H. V. Esmond</NAME> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Birds of a Feather</TITLE>,</TINTERTEXTUALITY> whose chief role was an <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">old Jew, grand, petty, noble, and inglorious, generous and impossibly mean&mdash;but really a great character.</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE></QUOTE> NJ herself had fancied acting the role of <TCHARACTERNAME>Jacob Ussher</TCHARACTERNAME>&apos;s sister, in the novel <TCHARACTERNAME>Grace Ussher</TCHARACTERNAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 167" DBREF="68825">167</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">She showed her finished manuscript to <NAME>Eva Moore</NAME> (widow of H. V. Esmond and herself an actress), who was not much impressed.</RRESPONSES> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PERSONAL"><PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>But the agent <NAME>Raymond Savage</NAME>, working for <ORGNAME STANDARD="Curtis Brown Ltd">Curtis Brown</ORGNAME>, took it on and placed it with <ORGNAME>Thornton Butterworth</ORGNAME>. Savage became NJ&apos;s personal friend.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 168" DBREF="68825">168</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TCHARACTERNAME>Jacob Ussher</TCHARACTERNAME> begins as the son of a very poor family in the <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="London" REG="East End">East End of London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a land inhabited by men and women who, whatever they are, have no Saxon blood in their veins,</QUOTE> although many of them come from Germany.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Jacob Ussher 1973, 7" DBREF="69246">7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGPLACE> Jacob <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="work for a living">begins earning at twelve, collecting and selling used newspapers,</TMOTIF> and though his mother, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Cockney convert to Judaism</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, wants him to learn a trade, his father, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Jewish tailor</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, approves of his decision to <TPLOT>set up instead as a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">trader in an extremely small way, with a barrow</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. Jacob gradually makes himself wealthy, and marries a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>beautiful Christian woman</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. Later, however, his wife <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="elopement">elopes</TMOTIF> with a nobleman to escape her <TMOTIF>loveless marriage</TMOTIF>. Jacob quarrels with his co-religionists when they reprove him for his failures in <TTHEMETOPIC>Jewish religious observance</TTHEMETOPIC>. His sister, Grace, keeps house for him, but he quarrels constantly with her, and they live together while hating each other. Jacob gets a twisted satisfaction from giving to Christian causes</TPLOT> (purely to annoy his fellow Jews) or to the town whose local duke married his divorced wife. Through acts of spite he makes a name for himself as a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">broad-minded philanthropist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.</TPLOT></P><P><TPLOT>His <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">daughter, Leah, the apple of his eye</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="inheritance">inherits his business sense</TMOTIF> but rebels against him. She chooses to love her <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>father&apos;s secretary, <TCHARACTERNAME>Rupert Heringham</TCHARACTERNAME>, a weak man</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who will not challenge her <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="woman in power">gradual and stealthy assumption of power</TMOTIF>. Indeed, they both recognize that her love for him is essentially maternal. Leah becomes independently wealthy through investing in stocks, but to do so she <TTHEMETOPIC>forges a cheque</TTHEMETOPIC> from her father, thus giving him the power to wreck her life. However, he chooses not to do this, and gestures of love and reconciliation follow. Leah and Rupert are promised a<TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="happy ending"> happy marriage</TMOTIF> and sunshiny future,</TPLOT> while Jacob accompanies his sister to the synagogue on the feast of Yom Kippur.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Further pre-war novels by NJ which are not discussed here include <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Rock and Sand</TITLE>, 1926, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Power</TITLE>, 1927, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Plough</TITLE>, 1928, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Seen Unknown</TITLE>, 1931 (another Jewish novel), <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Roots</TITLE>, 1931, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Props</TITLE>, 1932, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Groping</TITLE>, 1933, and <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL"><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Time Piece</TITLE>, 1936 (set in <PLACE><REGION>Yorkshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>).</TSETTINGPLACE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Man who Found Himself</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69205" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, The Man Who Found Himself, 1929"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1929-03-21" CERTAINTY="BY">By late March 1929</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PDEDICATION>NJ published a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Man who Found Himself</TITLE>; she dedicated it to <NAME>Olivia Etherington-Smith</NAME>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">to whom . . . the North country is&mdash;Home</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Man Who 1973, prelims" DBREF="69247">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> as it is to the novel&apos;s hero.</PDEDICATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1416 (21 March 1929): 229" DBREF="54246">(21 March 1929): 229</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PEDITIONS>She revised this work for a <ORGNAME STANDARD="Pan">Pan Books</ORGNAME> edition of 1952.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The book is headed by a quotation from <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">As You Like It</TITLE><NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William"></NAME>: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Cupid hath clapped him on the shoulder.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Man Who 1973, prelims" DBREF="69247" QTDIN="QTDINYES">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY> It opens with <TCHARACTERNAME>Billie Briscoe</TCHARACTERNAME>, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">music-hall comedian</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, hating himself, hating his profession, thinking of a comic as a clown and a clown as a performing dog or monkey. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Something had snapped,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Man Who 1973, 22" DBREF="69247">22</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> though the word <SOCALLED>breakdown</SOCALLED> is never used. Prescribed a restful holiday in the country, Billie resolves to shed his identity altogether. <TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PRESENT"><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE">In the north, among the hills and forests where at first he is deathly bored, Billie tries being a gentleman and tries being a carpenter, and finds love.</TSETTINGPLACE></TSETTINGDATE></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="INFORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO">This novel received a vote as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the best book [that is, <QUOTE DIRECT="N">the greatest</QUOTE>] you have ever read</QUOTE> (no reasons given) in response to a question posted on <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Yahoo! Answers</TITLE> in 2007.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Yahoo! Answers" DBREF="69206"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Beloved Physician</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104710" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, The Beloved Physician, 1930"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1930-03-13">13 March 1930</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PDEDICATION>NJ issued a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Beloved Physician</TITLE>, dedicated to <NAME>Ethel Bentham</NAME>, a fellow <ORGNAME STANDARD="Labour Party">Labour Party</ORGNAME> member, as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the really and rightly Beloved Physician.</QUOTE></PDEDICATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1467 (13 March 1930): 211" DBREF="54246">(13 March 1930): 211</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 205" DBREF="68825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">205</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The title is a phrase used to describe the evangelist <NAME STANDARD="Luke, Saint">St Luke</NAME>.</TINTERTEXTUALITY> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">This seems to have been the last novel that NJ published through <ORGNAME>Thornton Butterworth</ORGNAME> before switching to <ORGNAME>Hutchinson</ORGNAME>.</PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>According to the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Feminist Companion</TITLE>, this volume focuses <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">more on the love-life than the profession of its <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">doctor-heroine</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Honour Come Back</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69207" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Honour Come Back, 1935"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1935-04-18" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid-April 1935</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">In <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Honour Come Back</TITLE> NJ imagined a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">young man abnormally sensitive to the sufferings of others</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, and the effect on him of fighting in the <TOPIC STANDARD="World War One">First World War</TOPIC>.</TSETTINGDATE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1733 (18 April 1935): 256" DBREF="54246">(18 April 1935): 256</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TCHARACTERNAME>Michael Benham</TCHARACTERNAME> seems to enact the ancient Jewish belief in the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">scapegoat</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who bears the sins of the world. <TPLOT>Born into a family of <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>professional soldiers</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, he hates the infliction of pain and antagonizes his father by his horror of <TTHEMETOPIC>hunting and shooting</TTHEMETOPIC>. When the <TOPIC STANDARD="First World War">Great War</TOPIC> breaks out he enlists under age, gets a commission, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="rescue">and <TTHEMETOPIC>wins a VC</TTHEMETOPIC> for his intrepidity in leading a party to rescue a wounded man caught on the wire: for Michael it was easier to risk his life than to listen to the man&apos;s screams.</TMOTIF> <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">But he gradually comes to believe that he is solely responsible for all the suffering around him; that the war and all its destruction is happening to punish him, and without him would cease.</TMOTIF> His <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="madness">delusion</TMOTIF> is confirmed when he deserts and the Armistice immediately follows. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">He loses his memory and adopts a new, <PLACE><GEOG REG="Italy">Italian</GEOG></PLACE> identity. In this other life he gradually acquires <TTHEMETOPIC>spiritual strength</TTHEMETOPIC>, and he recovers and finds he can bear his past.</TSETTINGPLACE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1733 (18 April 1935): 256" DBREF="54246">(18 April 1935): 256</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> judged this <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a powerful and deftly constructed study, shot with a fine poetic quality and exhibiting a deep understanding of a troubled soul.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1733 (18 April 1935): 256" DBREF="54246">(18 April 1935): 256</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRECOGNITIONS><RPENALTIES><PEDITIONS><PPLACEOFPUBLICATION>When published in the <PLACE><GEOG>USA</GEOG></PLACE> in the same year,</PPLACEOFPUBLICATION></PEDITIONS> the book was awarded the <RRECOGNITIONNAME>Eichelberger Prize</RRECOGNITIONNAME> for <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">services to humanity</QUOTE>&mdash;<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 151" DBREF="68930">151</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>but this proved an embarrassment rather than an honour, since the prize was to be shared with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mein Kampf</TITLE> by <NAME>Adolf Hitler</NAME>. <PATTITUDES>NJ declined the award <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">with humility and regret</QUOTE>; she observed that it was impossible for her to accept, not because she was a Jew but because she could not inflict this linkage on her Jewish readers and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">kind, good and generous friends.</QUOTE></PATTITUDES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 152" DBREF="68930" QTDIN="QTDINYES">152</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RPENALTIES></RRECOGNITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Barren Metal</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="68615" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Barren Metal, 1936"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1936-03-21" CERTAINTY="BY">By late March 1936</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">NJ published a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Barren Metal</TITLE> (a title taken from a speech of Antonio in <NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William">Shakespeare</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Merchant of Venice</TITLE>).</TINTERTEXTUALITY></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1781 (21 March 1936): 242" DBREF="54246">(21 March 1936): 242</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Catalogue" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The <NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William">Shakespeare</NAME> allusion is curious and suggestive. Antonio is replying to Shylock&apos;s famous speech claiming humanity for Jews; he justifies his own racial or religious hostility, and suggests that usury can only be pracised on an enemy.</TINTERTEXTUALITY> In Jacob&apos;s story <TCHARACTERNAME>Meyer Pardo</TCHARACTERNAME>, one of a family of <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">German Jews who have emigrated to England, is a tailor</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, who got his start in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="London" REG="East End">London</SETTLEMENT>&apos;s poor East End<REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> making bunting (chains of flags) for <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Queen Victoria</NAME>&apos;s jubilee</TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1781 (21 March 1936): 242" DBREF="54246">(21 March 1936): 242</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TPLOT>After growing <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">rich and successful</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> he becomes involved in <TTHEMETOPIC>shady dealings with crooked (Gentile) businessmen</TTHEMETOPIC>, which he never really understood, and serves a <TTHEMETOPIC>sentence in prison</TTHEMETOPIC>. His wife, <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Pardo, Rachel">Rachel</TCHARACTERNAME>, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="financial ruin">reduced from riches to poverty</TMOTIF>, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="work for a living">goes into the dressmaking business herself</TMOTIF> and builds her own success and wealth, only to lose it all again at a later stage. Of their two sons, David the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>intellectual</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> goes into films, while Isaac, or Ike, whose ambition is wealth, makes his own <TTHEMETOPIC>tailoring establishment so classy that it is more like a club than a shop</TTHEMETOPIC>, and marries the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>hatefully snobbish, artificially blonde</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> Helen, who <TTHEMETOPIC>denies her own family&apos;s Jewish roots</TTHEMETOPIC> and prefers to call her husband George.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 158-61" DBREF="68930">158-61</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO"><NAME>Paul Bailey</NAME> called this novel <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">thumpingly terrible</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 158" DBREF="68930">158</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TCHARACTERIZATION>and used it to demonstrate Jacob&apos;s habit of signalling to her reader which characters to approve and which to disapprove.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 161" DBREF="68930">161</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TCHARACTERIZATION><TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="NONSTANDARDENGLISH"><TCHARACTERIZATION>He was not impressed by NJ&apos;s handling here of non-standard English. When a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Yiddish-speaking Jew</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Cockney</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> and a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Yorkshireman</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE></QUOTE> converse together he found the results nightmarish: their various forms of English are so rendered that the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">apostrophes come at the hapless reader like shrapnel.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 135" DBREF="68930">135</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TCHARACTERIZATION></TTECHNIQUES></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="NONSTANDARDENGLISH">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> reviewer had suggested that footnotes would have been helpful.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1781 (21 March 1936): 242" DBREF="54246">(21 March 1936): 242</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TTECHNIQUES> The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> also felt that the book was stronger on atmosphere (with descriptions of <TTHEMETOPIC>ghettoes, pogroms and persecution</TTHEMETOPIC>) than on story.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1781 (21 March 1936): 242" DBREF="54246">(21 March 1936): 242</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">This Porcelain Clay</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69208" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, This Porcelain Clay, 1939"></TEXTSCOPE><TEXTUALFEATURES><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1939-03-25" CERTAINTY="BY">By late March 1939</DATE><CHRONPROSE>In a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">This Porcelain Clay</TITLE>, NJ related the story of a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">brilliant and driven</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> man named <TCHARACTERNAME>Louis Silver</TCHARACTERNAME>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1938 (25 March 1939): 180" DBREF="54246">(25 March 1939): 180</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1939 (1 April 1939): 187" DBREF="54246">(1 April 1939): 187</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT>Silver&apos;s father, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>self-made man</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, sends Louis and his brother David to a good school, then dies. Louis becomes a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">fruit-seller and bookmaker, and rises to wealth and power</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> while supporting his mother and sister. Once he has become rich and powerful he belatedly awakens to values in life which he has always ignored, and tries to remake a new and less materialistic self.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1939 (1 April 1939): 187" DBREF="54246">(1 April 1939): 187</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Full Meridian</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69209" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Full Meridian, 1939"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1939-11-04" CERTAINTY="BY">By November 1939</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">NJ set her <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Full Meridian</TITLE> in <PLACE><REGION>Yorkshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, with a protagonist, <TCHARACTERNAME>Ann Harrington</TCHARACTERNAME>, who decisively ends a <TMOTIF>bad marriage</TMOTIF>, brings up three children alone, and becomes a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">business success</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.</TSETTINGPLACE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1970 (4 November 1939): 639" DBREF="54246">(4 November 1939): 639</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1972 (18 November 1939): 667" DBREF="54246">(18 November 1939): 667</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT>Ann&apos;s world is shattered when her husband comes back full of <TTHEMETOPIC>anger and revenge</TTHEMETOPIC>. He destroys the life of her son, but is powerless against her, his two daughters, and the youngest child, another daughter, whom Ann has borne after finding love.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1972 (18 November 1939): 667" DBREF="54246">(18 November 1939): 667</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>As Ellington Gray</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="70787" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Saffroned Bridesails, 1928"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1928-03-29" CERTAINTY="BY">By late March 1928</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PAUTHORSHIP AUTHORNAMETYPE="PSEUDONYMOUS"><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">Under her pseudonym of <SOCALLED>Ellington Gray</SOCALLED>, NJ published a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Saffroned Bridesails</TITLE>, a phrase which she found in a poem by <NAME STANDARD="Kipling, Rudyard">Kipling</NAME>.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></PAUTHORSHIP></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1365 (29 March 1928): 241" DBREF="54246">(29 March 1928): 241</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 240-1" DBREF="68825">240-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">She wrote to <NAME STANDARD="Kipling, Rudyard">Kipling</NAME> to enquire the meaning of the words and he reproved her for using them without understanding them.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 240-1" DBREF="68825">240-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT>The male protagonist, named Sandy, is a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">philanderer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, who, however, finds true love in the end.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1365 (29 March 1928): 241" DBREF="54246">(29 March 1928): 241</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>The Gollantz Novels</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="68612" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, &quot;That Wild Lie&mdash;&quot;, 1930"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="PERIOD"><DATE VALUE="1930-08-29" CERTAINTY="BY">By late August 1930</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">NJ issued a <TGENRE GENRENAME="BILDUNGSROMAN">bildungsroman</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">That Wild Lie&mdash;</QUOTE></TITLE>, in which <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Gollantz, Emmanuel,, the elder">Emmanuel Gollantz</TCHARACTERNAME> emigrates from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vienna</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Austria"></GEOG></PLACE> and makes good in Victorian <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>. On his <TTHEMETOPIC>family firm</TTHEMETOPIC> she then centred a hugely successful series or saga.</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1491 (29 August 1930): 679" DBREF="54246">(29 August 1930): 679</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>The respected London publishing house of <NAME>Victor Gollancz</NAME> was then about three years old.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PCONTRACT><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">This novel was published by <ORGNAME>Hutchinson</ORGNAME>, to whom NJ moved from <ORGNAME STANDARD="Thornton Butterworth">Butterworth</ORGNAME> as a result of the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">lucrative, long-standing contract</QUOTE> negotiated with Hutchinson by her agent, <NAME>Raymond Savage</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 147" DBREF="68930">147</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></PCONTRACT> <PEDITIONS>As the series took root and proliferated like the Gollantzes themselves, this volume became number two and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Young Emmanuel</TITLE>, published second in 1932, became volume three. It was in 1935 that NJ turned back to launch her story with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Founder of the House</TITLE>, which fills in two generations before the first Emmanuel, and which thereafter stood at the head of the series.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The series deals with <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>largely-assimilated Jews of the upper ranks of the bourgeoisie</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>: some of their <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>aristocratic clientele</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> accept them more or less as equals, while others scorn them. In <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">That Wild Lie&mdash;</QUOTE></TITLE> The earlier Emmanuel leaves for England primed with advice about how Englishmen in general dislike and fear Jews, but how if once an Englishman has come to accept a particular Jew as straight and honest, he will trust him utterly.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 156-7" DBREF="68930">156-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Although the advisor warns him that an Englishman hates <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Jew who is ashamed of being a Jew</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 157" DBREF="68930" QTDIN="QTDINYES">157</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Emmanuel the elder, who begins with <TTHEMETOPIC>Viennese culture</TTHEMETOPIC> <TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="NONSTANDARDENGLISH">but without fluent English language, goes on to refashion himself as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">rich English gentleman art dealer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 156" DBREF="68930">156</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> His command of the English language, however, remains imperfect until the end.</TTECHNIQUES></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104705" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Four Generations, 1934"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1934-03-22" CERTAINTY="BY">By late March 1934</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">With <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Four Generations</TITLE> (the third to appear in NJ&apos;s series of <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE> about the Jewish Gollantz family, but eventually the fourth in the order of the story they cover), Jacob began to achieve wide recognition.</RRESPONSES></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1677 (22 March 1934): 212" DBREF="54246">(22 March 1934): 212</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Naomi Jacob" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT>Here <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Gollantz, Emmanuel,, the younger">Emmanuel</TCHARACTERNAME> the younger, an eldest son in the Gollantz family of <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>successful antique dealers</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, makes a <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="happy marriage">fashionable (but happy) marriage</TMOTIF> which endures for only two years before he meets once again his first love, an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">opera singer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> ten years older than himself named Juliet. For her he throws away everything in his successful life. She <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="death of heroine">dies a year into their idyllically happy marriage</TMOTIF>, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="orphan">leaving him with a child to bring up</TMOTIF>.</TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO"><TTONESTYLE>The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> found this a romantic story somewhat at odds with the soberly naturalistic style in which it is told,</TTONESTYLE> and suggested that NJ ought to have presented her protagonist for the reader&apos;s sympathy rather than allowing him to be seen as a hero.</RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</TITLE> called the book <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">essentially a late version of the Edwardian marriage-problem novel, <TTONESTYLE>with a modern glaze of frankness and a taste of bitterness.</TTONESTYLE></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Naomi Jacob" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1677 (22 March 1934): 212" DBREF="54246">(22 March 1934): 212</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="68585" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, The Founder of the House, 1935"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1935-11-02" CERTAINTY="BY">By November 1935</DATE><CHRONPROSE>In <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Founder of the House</TITLE> NJ produced an <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">opening volume</TGENRE> for her saga of the Jewish Gollantzes, whose character traits persist through the generations in a way that the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Oxford Dictionary of National Biography">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</TITLE> finds typical of Edwardian fiction.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1761 (2 November 1935): 682" DBREF="54246">(2 November 1935): 682</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Naomi Jacob" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>This novel encompasses three generations. <TPLOT><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST"><TCHARACTERNAME>Abraham Gollantz</TCHARACTERNAME> enters the story in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE> in the 1790s, having travelled from Rotterdam to learn the business of art dealing from <TCHARACTERNAME>Fernando Meldola</TCHARACTERNAME>, his father&apos;s oldest friend, an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Italian Jew</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who lives in Paris with his beautiful niece, <TCHARACTERNAME>Miriam Lousada</TCHARACTERNAME>. Abraham is <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>intensely ambitious, and turns out to be not above sharp practice</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. He <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="seduction">seduces</TMOTIF> Miriam (whom he later marries) and hires out his expertise to help <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Napoleon I,, Emperor of France">Napoleon</NAME> despoil <PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE> of its art treasures</TTHEMETOPIC>. He dies of heart disease before his son Hermann is born. <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Gollantz, Herman">Hermann</TCHARACTERNAME> grows up and moves the business, Meldola and Partner, to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vienna</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Austria"></GEOG></PLACE>.</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE> He suffers agonies as a young man for love of a Christian woman, shares a moment of attraction with a princess, and finally marries <TCHARACTERNAME>Rachel Hirsch</TCHARACTERNAME>&mdash;only after his mother has provoked him to propose by pretending to be about to embark on a second marriage herself, with a man her son despises. She knew he would have to confide his anxiety to someone, and from confidence would spring love.</TPLOT></P><P>The family has its troubles. <TPLOT>Rachel&apos;s brother Ishmael turns out to be even more prone to bend the rules of ethics than was Abraham Gollantz, and indulges in large scale <TTHEMETOPIC>forgery</TTHEMETOPIC>. (The <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>bad brother</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> is something of a motif in the series as a whole.) Hermann&apos;s son Marcus is drowned when the ice breaks as he is skating, and his brother <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Gollantz, Emmanuel,, the elder">Emmanuel</TCHARACTERNAME> is left with lasting <TTHEMETOPIC>emotional scars</TTHEMETOPIC> from having been unable to save him. Emmanuel&apos;s career is repeatedly ruffled by the experience of having aristocratic women fall in love with him, and meanwhile the business declines. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">This novel touches on his move to England, but notes that on arrival he <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">thought <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> the most gloomy place he had ever seen.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Founder 1973, 288" DBREF="69248">288</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He nevertheless establishes himself and flourishes there and finds a woman, Juliana, to love and marry.</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE></TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="68613" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Private Gollantz, 1943"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1943-05-" CERTAINTY="BY">By May 1943</DATE><CHRONPROSE>NJ pursued her Jewish family saga in a fifth, wartime <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">Private</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> Gollantz</TITLE> (featuring <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Gollantz, Emmanuel,, the younger">Emmanuel Gollantz</TCHARACTERNAME> the younger on army service), <PCIRCULATION>which reached its 75th thousand copy sold in 1944 and its 100th thousand in 1945.</PCIRCULATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2152 (1 May 1943): 205" DBREF="54246">(1 May 1943): 205</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT>Emmanuel the younger, the private of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Private Gollantz</TITLE>, joins up in the ranks and is later promoted to <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">lieutenant and eventually to major</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.</TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69267" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Gollantz: London, Paris, Milan, 1948"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1948-09-" CERTAINTY="AFTER">Later 1948</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PDEDICATION>NJ dedicated her latest Gollantz <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">instalment</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Gollantz: London, Paris, Milan</TITLE>, in September from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Fasano">Fasano</SETTLEMENT> (close to her own home on <REGION>Lake Garda</REGION> in <GEOG REG="Italy">Italy</GEOG></PLACE>) to two <SOCALLED>kind friends</SOCALLED> named Isabella and Dario.</PDEDICATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Gollantz London, 1974, prelims, 253" DBREF="69268">prelims, 253</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>This book became number six in the sequence. In 1952 and 1953 NJ published <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">The Gollantz Saga</TITLE>, which incorporates in two volumes the six titles published so far.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Gollantz: London, Paris, Milan</TITLE> opens with <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">Major</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Gollantz, Emmanuel,, the younger">Emmanuel Gollantz</TCHARACTERNAME> supervising the <TTHEMETOPIC>dismantling of an Italian prisoner-of-war camp</TTHEMETOPIC> which he has been in charge of for almost three years. (He thinks of <TTHEMETOPIC>Italians</TTHEMETOPIC> in essentialist terms, as an <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">old race, but a young people, frequently very <EMPH>naughty</EMPH>, rarely actually wicked.</QUOTE>)<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Gollantz London, 1974, 11" DBREF="69268">11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> By the end of the novel his experience in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Private Gollantz</TITLE> has been linked up with his experience in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Four Generations</TITLE>. He is now Sir Emmanuel Gollantz, Baronet, and after marrying in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE> he is on his second honeymoon (on <PLACE><REGION>Lake Garda</REGION><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>!) with Viva, his first wife, with whom he has finally found happiness long after he left her for his short-lived great love, Juliet.</TSETTINGPLACE> His son with Juliet, Simeon, is doing well and is also about to marry. A <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">little, rather shabbily dressed Jew</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Gollantz London, 1974, 248" DBREF="69268">248</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> from Holland has turned up for the wedding, in part so that he can enthuse about the gathering of distinguished relations and friends from apparently all over Europe (France, Austria, Italy), and provoke a comment from a listening Scotswoman wishing that this <TTHEMETOPIC>international friendliness</TTHEMETOPIC> could <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">spread to governments and diplomatic missions.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Gollantz London, 1974, 249" DBREF="69268">249</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="68614" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Gollantz and Partners, 1958"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1958-01-10" CERTAINTY="AFTER">Early 1958</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PDEDICATION>NJ brought her Jewish family chronicle to an end with a seventh <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Gollantz and Partners</TITLE>, dedicated to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><NAME STANDARD="Benn, Evelyn">Evelyn</NAME> (Mrs Eustace Benn).</QUOTE></PDEDICATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2915 (10 January 1958): 13" DBREF="54246">(10 January 1958): 13</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Gollantz and Partners, Prelims" DBREF="69269">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="long-lost relation">This novel opens with a young man, <TCHARACTERNAME>Charles Emmanuel Gollantz</TCHARACTERNAME>, presenting hinself to <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Gollantz, Emmanuel,, the younger">Emmanuel the younger</TCHARACTERNAME> (who is now, of course, old). Charles claims to be the legitimate son of Emmanuel&apos;s ne&apos;er-do-well brother <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Gollantz, Julian">Julian</TCHARACTERNAME>, and has the papers to prove it. He is therefore older than Julian&apos;s two already-known sons by his second marriage, and his <SOCALLED>discovery</SOCALLED> occasions much family crisis.</TMOTIF> By the end of the novel he is thoroughly settled into the family: he and Emmanuel&apos;s son <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Gollantz, Simeon">Simeon</TCHARACTERNAME> are like a pair of good brothers, and each is entering on <TTHEMETOPIC>happy domesticity</TTHEMETOPIC> and on continuing the family, while Max, son of Julian, has proved himself a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>bad apple</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> and has been sidelined. In his going he provokes a speech from Emmanuel about the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">curious . . . <TTHEMETOPIC>hatred of Jews</TTHEMETOPIC> [that] runs through our family,</QUOTE> appearing in an uncle of Emmanuel, in Emmanuel&apos;s brother Julian, and now in Julian&apos;s son. These men regard their Jewish blood as shameful and are deficient in that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TTHEMETOPIC>pride of race</TTHEMETOPIC> that every decent Jew should feel.</QUOTE> Emmanuel holds that this pride <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">may be diluted, but no one can eradicate it.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Gollantz and Partners, 1974, 254" DBREF="69269">254</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Life-Writing</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><TGENREISSUE>NJ&apos;s many volumes of reminiscences contain elements of <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">autobiography</TGENRE>, but often focus on <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">stories about other people</TGENRE>, particularly those belonging to the <TTHEMETOPIC>theatre world</TTHEMETOPIC>. The <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Feminist Companion</TITLE> calls their contents <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">memoirs, <TGENRE GENRENAME="ESSAY">essays</TGENRE>, <TGENRE GENRENAME="APHORISM">commonplaces</TGENRE> and <TGENRE GENRENAME="CONDUCTLITERATURE">advice</TGENRE>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TGENREISSUE> Her dates are vague and her facts not always self-consistent, but her handling of anecdote is excellent.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><SOCALLED>Me</SOCALLED> Books</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104707" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Me: A Chronicle about Other People, 1933"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1933-09-07" CERTAINTY="BY">By early September 1933</DATE><CHRONPROSE>NJ published her first <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">memoir</TGENRE>. Entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me: A Chronicle about Other People</TITLE>, <PCIRCULATION>it soon reached its thirteen thousandth copy in sales.</PCIRCULATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1649 (7 September 1933): 591" DBREF="54246">(7 September 1933): 591</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, Prelims" DBREF="68825">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PDEDICATION>Her <TGENRE GENRENAME="DEDICATION">dedication</TGENRE>, dated from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Sirmione"><SIC CORR="Sirmione">Sermione</SIC></SETTLEMENT>, <REGION REG="Lake Garda">Lago di Garda</REGION>, <GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE>, is typically upbeat. It reads (with the names in capitals): <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">To all those people who have helped me, taught me, made me laugh, and shown me what a good place the world can be, and especially to <NAME STANDARD="Simeone, Henrietta Carlotta Francesca Maria">Henrietta Carlotta Francesca Maria Simeone (Simmy)</NAME> and . . . a very gallant little Chinese gentleman [her Pekinese], whose real name is Hi Ling Choo Foo, but who is always called Sam.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, Prelims" DBREF="68825">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PDEDICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="IMAGERY">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Overture</TITLE> (which envisages the coming book as the performance of a play)</TTECHNIQUES> asks, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Why should I try to remember anything but the good things?</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 18" DBREF="68825">18</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Thus NJ describes her native <TTHEMETOPIC><PLACE><REGION>Yorkshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> and her mother&apos;s family</TTHEMETOPIC> as quirky and lovable, and her <TTHEMETOPIC>teaching of slum children</TTHEMETOPIC> as something she excelled at, although she hated the <TTHEMETOPIC>repressive atmosphere of the church school</TTHEMETOPIC>. She never mentions her father or discusses her Jewish heritage. But in the several chapters she gives to the <TTHEMETOPIC>music-hall</TTHEMETOPIC> at its zenith, the performers whom she describes in detail include <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>John Lawson</NAME> from Lancashire, who specialized in Jewish sketches</TTHEMETOPIC>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 72-3" DBREF="68825">72-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and she writes that <TTHEMETOPIC>Jews in show business</TTHEMETOPIC> drive a hard bargain and are good to work with, but that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the man who is palpably a Jew, and denies the fact, is a person unworthy of your trust,</QUOTE> even though the reason for his deception is <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">all the stupid and loathsome stories</QUOTE> that denigrate Jews.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 89" DBREF="68825">89</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She gives a chapter, warm with admiration, to <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Marie Lloyd</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>. She finds space to protest about <TTHEMETOPIC>cruelty in the training of animals for the stage</TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 98-107, 92-3" DBREF="68825">98-107, 92-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She writes in energetic and amusing detail about her <TTHEMETOPIC>war work</TTHEMETOPIC>, and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">purposely omitting the horrible days, the dreadful nights, and all the heartbreaking things which happened</QUOTE> (young men marching away to war, ambulances receiving them back), <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">because we all remember them.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 126" DBREF="68825">126</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><TTONESTYLE>Her theatrical memoirs are unchronological, unsorted, anecdotal, and vivid.</TTONESTYLE> She enjoys relating <TTHEMETOPIC>clashes or conflicts in which she comes out on top</TTHEMETOPIC>. She describes herself as solidly patriotic, though not <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one of the Union-Jack-waving Britishers</QUOTE> who think their country the best in the world.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 256" DBREF="68825">256</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She explicitly claims, too, to be non-snobbish, though alert to the distinctions of class: one of the attitudes she snubs is that it might be a drawback to life in Italy to have no neighbours of her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">own class</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 276" DBREF="68825">276</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She says she hates to end a book because she then thinks of all the things she could have put into it and did not, and proceeds to end with a rag-bag of further anecdotes. The last of all are stories of <TTHEMETOPIC>unbidden kindnesses</TTHEMETOPIC>, to prove Jacob&apos;s point that most people are kindly at heart,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 279ff" DBREF="68825">279ff</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">and she brings down the curtain with two lines from <NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William">Shakespeare</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Richard II</TITLE> about remembering her good friends.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 189-90" DBREF="68825">189-90</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">An early review found this performance <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[f]ull of vivid snapshots of personages, literary, theatrical, and political,</QUOTE> and prophesied that it deserved to be and would be a best-seller.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1649 (7 September 1933): 591; 1656 (26 October 1933): 723" DBREF="54246">(7 September 1933): 591; (26 October 1933): 723</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES"><NAME>Paul Bailey</NAME> observed recently that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">some of her many readers must have been bewildered by the absence of</QUOTE> NJ&apos;s father from her pages.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 80" DBREF="68930">80</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104708" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Me&mdash; In the Kitchen, 1935"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1935-06-27" CERTAINTY="BY">By late June 1935</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TTONESTYLE>NJ published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me&mdash;In the Kitchen</TITLE>, which is by all accounts comically anglocentric for a <TGENRE GENRENAME="COOKBOOK">cookery book</TGENRE> by a resident of <PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE>.</TTONESTYLE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1743 (27 June 1935): 417" DBREF="54246">(27 June 1935): 417</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 153" DBREF="68930">153</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>She highlights <TTHEMETOPIC>recipes for Yorkshire pudding and those suet puddings</TTHEMETOPIC> known as <SOCALLED>stodge</SOCALLED>, and when <TTHEMETOPIC>pasta</TTHEMETOPIC> is cooked she wants it lengthily boiled. She addresses herself to a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">nameless young housewife (and later mother) whose chief aim in life is to placate her husband</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, George (who never enters the kitchen during cooking), so that the way she prepares him to receive a new dish seems as important as the food itself.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 153-5" DBREF="68930">153-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> (whose reviewer evidently belonged to the old school) singled out the useful advice on <TTHEMETOPIC>cooking kippers</TTHEMETOPIC> and <TTHEMETOPIC>making tea</TTHEMETOPIC> (<QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a task which everyone thinks he understands, but few can perform wholly satisfactorily</QUOTE>), and thought the book&apos;s instructions were so simple as to be well adapted to cooking in a studio, flat or bungalow rather than a proper house, but that it could be usefully followed in a conventional kitchen <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">once the conventional cook had recovered from the shocks it would give her.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1743 (27 June 1935): 417" DBREF="54246">(27 June 1935): 417</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Next in NJ&apos;s series of <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">memoirs</TGENRE> came <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me&mdash;Again</TITLE>, 1937, <PAUTHORSHIP>and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">More about Me</TITLE>, 1939 (of which a 1946 reprint was published as by <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Naomi Ellington Jacob <QUOTE DIRECT="N">Ellington Gray</QUOTE> pseud.</QUOTE>).</PAUTHORSHIP><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Catalogue" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69210" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Me&mdash;in War Time, 1940"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1940-12-14" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid-December 1940</DATE><CHRONPROSE>NJ lost no time in getting into print her <TGENRE GENRENAME="TRAVELWRITING"><TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">account</TGENRE></TGENRE> of her <TTHEMETOPIC>evacuation from <PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE> to <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC> during the <TOPIC>Second World War</TOPIC>: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me&mdash;in War Time</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2028 (14 December 1940): 627" DBREF="54246">(14 December 1940): 627</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="ADFEMINAM"><TTONESTYLE>The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> treated this book as an embodiment of its author&apos;s personality, resembling <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a confidential talk by the fireside, the talk of a mature and kindly woman who looks on war as a vast insanity</QUOTE> but this war as needing to be fought. The review praised the book&apos;s common-sense comment, breadth of vision, and racy or nostalgic anecdotes. Jacob, it said, had <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the mind of a shrewd woman of the world and the heart of a little child.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2028 (14 December 1940): 627" DBREF="54246">(14 December 1940): 627</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TTONESTYLE></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>In another <TGENRE GENRENAME="TRAVELWRITING"><TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">memoir</TGENRE></TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me and the <PLACE><REGION>Mediterranean</REGION></PLACE></TITLE>, published in 1945, NJ wrote about <TTHEMETOPIC>working for <ORGNAME STANDARD="Entertainments National Service Association">ENSA Welfare</ORGNAME> in 1943-4 in <PLACE><AREA REG="Africa">North Africa</AREA> (<GEOG>Morocco</GEOG></PLACE> and <PLACE><GEOG>Algeria</GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE>), Italy, and <PLACE><REGION>Sicily</REGION><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>. It was followed by <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me&mdash;Over There</TITLE>, 1947, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me and Mine: (You and Yours)</TITLE> (about <TTHEMETOPIC>animals</TTHEMETOPIC>, with a preface by <NAME>W. H. Elliott</NAME>), 1949, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me&mdash;Looking Back</TITLE>, 1950.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2275 (8 September 1945): 431" DBREF="54246">(8 September 1945): 431</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Catalogue" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="68618" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Robert, Nana, and&mdash;Me: A Family Chronicle, 1952"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1952-05-09" CERTAINTY="BY">By 9 May 1952</DATE><CHRONPROSE>NJ published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Robert, Nana and&mdash;Me: A <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">Family <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">Chronicle</TGENRE></TGENRE></TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2623 (9 May 1952): 315" DBREF="54246">(9 May 1952): 315</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>This book ostensibly deals with three lives: those of NJ&apos;s maternal grandfather, <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Robert Ellington Collinson</NAME>, of her <NAME STANDARD="Collinson, Nana">mother</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> (the eldest of the three children whom he brought up after his first wife&apos;s early death), and of the author herself. In fact it also presents a detailed and unflattering picture of <TTHEMETOPIC>her <NAME STANDARD="Jacob, Samuel">father</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, who had been omitted from her first volume of autobiography, as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the worst husband and the nastiest father any wife or daughter could have.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 80" DBREF="68930">80</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">A blurb for this book said it had <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a story as moving and romantic as that of any of Miss Jacob&apos;s novels.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Trefusis, dustjacket" DBREF="12369">dustjacket</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> review praised the accounts of Jacob&apos;s grandfather and mother and indicated respect for her reticence about her parents&apos; marriage, or indeed her father&apos;s character (apart from her own experience of it as a small child): <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[t]o portray the havoc and misery caused by a close relation is a delicate matter.</QUOTE> It expressed regret that she had not been more forthcoming about herself.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2623 (9 May 1952): 315" DBREF="54246">(9 May 1952): 315</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>After this her <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">memoirs</TGENRE> continued indefatigably with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me&mdash;Likes and Dislikes</TITLE>, 1954, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me&mdash;Yesterday and Today</TITLE>, 1957, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me&mdash;and the Swans</TITLE> (about women she admired and respected, most of them <TTHEMETOPIC>actresses</TTHEMETOPIC>), 1963.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Catalogue" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Stags 11" DBREF="69211">11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69211" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Me&mdash;and the Stags, 1964"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1964-07-01">1 July 1964</DATE><CHRONPROSE>NJ&apos;s new publisher, <ORGNAME>William Kimber</ORGNAME>, marked her eightieth birthday by issuing her <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me&mdash;and the Stags</TITLE> (about men, mainly <TTHEMETOPIC>actors</TTHEMETOPIC>, a <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY"><TGENRE GENRENAME="SEQUEL"><TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">companion piece</TGENRE></TGENRE></TGENRE> to <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me&mdash;and the Swans</TITLE>, 1963, on women).</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 182" DBREF="68930">182</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Stags 11" DBREF="69211">11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>This title seems unusually prone to misrepresentation. Paul Bailey mistakenly calls it <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me&mdash;and the Stage</TITLE>, and the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">British Library Catalogue</TITLE> has (in 2011) an entry listing it as published in 1914: a mistake duly replicated by <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">OCLC WorldCat</TITLE>.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PDEDICATION>Jacob dedicated this book about men to two women, <NAME STANDARD="Du Maurier, Angela">Angela Du Maurier</NAME> (sister of the famous Daphne, and a novelist in her own right) and <NAME>Betty Seymour Hicks</NAME></PDEDICATION> (whose actor parents, <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Ellaline Terriss</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> and <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Sir Seymour Hicks</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, featured among the swans and stags respectively).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Stags, prelims, 79ff, dustjacket" DBREF="69211">prelims, 79ff, dustjacket</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> This time the first of her subjects was her <TTHEMETOPIC>parish priest at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Sirmione</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Lake Garda"></REGION><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>. She wrote that she expected to be attacked by critics <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">for having liked anyone at all,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Stags, 17ff, 11" DBREF="69211">17ff, 11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> but she probably missed the reviews, for she died only a couple of weeks after this book appeared.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104709" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Me&mdash;Thinking Things Over, 1964"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATESTRUCT CERTAINTY="C" VALUE="1964-10-"><SEASON VALUE="10" CERTAINTY="C">Autumn</SEASON> <YEAR VALUE="1964">1964</YEAR></DATESTRUCT><CHRONPROSE>A few months after her death, NJ&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Me&mdash;Thinking Things Over</TITLE> appeared in print, collecting her <TGENRE GENRENAME="SPEECH">talks</TGENRE> broadcast on the <ORGNAME STANDARD="BBC" REG="British Broadcasting Corporation">BBC</ORGNAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Woman&apos;s Hour</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 142" DBREF="68930">142</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>This volume, says the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Feminist Companion</TITLE>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">gallantly denies fear of age or death.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The following year, 1965, <NAME>James Norbury</NAME> published a life of her in highly-embellished style, fittingly entitled<TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Naomi Jacob; The Seven Ages of Me</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Lives of Others</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69905" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, &quot;Our Marie&quot; (Marie Lloyd): a Biography, 1936"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1936-04-07">7 April 1936</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PADVERTISING><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO">The book that NJ&apos;s biographer <NAME>Paul Bailey</NAME> considers the most durable of her works,</RRESPONSES> a <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">life</TGENRE> of the <TTHEMETOPIC>music-hall performer <NAME>Marie Lloyd</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Our Marie</TITLE>, was advertised as forthcoming on this day.</PADVERTISING></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1783 (4 April 1936): 295" DBREF="54246">(4 April 1936): 295</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 183" DBREF="68930">183</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME STANDARD="Bailey, Paul">Bailey</NAME> considers that although more recent biographers are more accurate (and although one of them, <NAME>Midge Gillies</NAME>, accuses NJ of romanticizing the music-hall), Jacob knew the audiences Lloyd played to&mdash;who could be rowdy and unforgiving but who were passionately loyal to the performers who won their love&mdash;and was able to catch the spirit of the age and the place.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 183-4" DBREF="68930">183-4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>In 1955 NJ published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Prince China">Prince China. By himself but dictated to Naomi Jacob</TITLE>, purportedly the <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">autobiography</TGENRE> of one of her <TTHEMETOPIC>Pekinese</TTHEMETOPIC>.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Broadcasting and Miscellaneous</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ made an additional career as a <TGENRE GENRENAME="SPEECH">public lecturer</TGENRE>; without any specialist expertise, she could express confident and articulate opinions on a wide range of topics. She was a regular and outspoken contributor to the <ORGNAME STANDARD="BBC" REG="British Broadcasting Corporation">BBC</ORGNAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Woman&apos;s Hour</TITLE>. <PEARNINGS>From both of these activities her earnings were high.</PEARNINGS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Furbank 8" DBREF="10711">8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>NJ once made some progress in <TGENRE GENRENAME="EDITING">editing</TGENRE> a book in <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">very <SOCALLED>German</SOCALLED> English</QUOTE> by an author of that nationality, but when he addressed her as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Dear Mother of my unborn child,</QUOTE> she dropped the commission.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 247" DBREF="68825">247</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PAUTHORSHIP COLLABORATION="COLLABORATIONYES">Collaborating with <NAME STANDARD="Robertson, James Constable">James C. Robertson</NAME>, she produced <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><TTHEMETOPIC>Opera</TTHEMETOPIC> in Italy</TITLE>, 1948,</PAUTHORSHIP> and on her own she published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Impressions from <TTHEMETOPIC><PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>, 1952. She contributed a <TGENRE GENRENAME="PREFATORYPIECE">foreword</TGENRE> to memoirs by the actor <NAME>Bransby Williams</NAME> in 1954.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Catalogue" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2748 (1 October 1954): 622" DBREF="54246">(1 October 1954): 622</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Novels by her Mother</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="70788" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Look at the Clock, 1939"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1939-05-27" CERTAINTY="BY">By late May 1939</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Look at the Clock: A <PLACE><REGION>Yorkshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> Novel</TITLE>, begun in Italy by NJ&apos;s mother, was published by <ORGNAME>Duckworth</ORGNAME> under the name of <SOCALLED><NAME STANDARD="Collinson, Nana">Nina Abbott</NAME></SOCALLED>, with a <TGENRE GENRENAME="PREFATORYPIECE">foreword</TGENRE> by Jacob.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1947 (27 May 1939): 317" DBREF="54246">(27 May 1939): 317</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 144" DBREF="68930">144</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PAUTHORSHIP COLLABORATION="COLLABORATIONYES">Jacob wrote up two more novels from notes left by her mother. These were published as <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Shadow Drama</TITLE>, 1940, by <SOCALLED><NAME STANDARD="Collinson, Nana">Nina Abbott</NAME></SOCALLED>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[a]rranged and edited . . . by her daughter, Naomi Jacob,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Balance Suspended</TITLE>, 1942.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 144" DBREF="68930">144</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PAUTHORSHIP></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Later Novels</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ&apos;s production rate barely slackened during her last years, whose harvest of <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE> included <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Heart of the House</TITLE>, 1951, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Late Lark Singing</TITLE>, 1952, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Morning Will Come</TITLE>, 1953, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Antonia</TITLE>, 1954, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Wind on the Heath</TITLE>, 1956, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">What&apos;s To Come</TITLE>, 1958, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Search for a Background</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Three Men and Jennie</TITLE>, both 1960, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">White Wool</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Great Black Oxen</TITLE>, both 1962. She also issued an omnibus volume of four already-published short novels, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Tales of the Broad Acres</TITLE>, 1955.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69225" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, The Irish Boy, A Romantic Biography, 1955"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1955-09-16" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid-September 1955</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TGENREISSUE><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">NJ included a number of actual personages in her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TGENRE GENRENAME="ROMANCE">romantic</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE></QUOTE> or <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORICAL">historical</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> about the eighteenth-century <TTHEMETOPIC>prodigy Irish singer <NAME>Michael Kelly</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Irish Boy, A Romantic Biography, The">The Irish Boy</TITLE>.</TSETTINGDATE></TGENREISSUE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2794 (16 September 1955): 533" DBREF="54246">(16 September 1955): 533</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 155" DBREF="68930">155</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TCHARACTERIZATION>Characters in this book (stereotypes all, according to Paul Bailey) include <NAME STANDARD="Haydn, Joseph">Haydn</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="Mozart, Wolfgang Amadeus">Mozart</NAME> (<QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a little, white-faced genius</QUOTE>), <NAME STANDARD="Casanova, Giacomo">Casanova</NAME> (possessor of a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">strange, twisted smile</QUOTE>), and the <NAME STANDARD="Stuart, Charles Edward">Young Pretender</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 155" DBREF="68930" QTDIN="QTDINYES">155</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TCHARACTERIZATION></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO"><NAME>Paul Bailey</NAME> comments that Kelly <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">merits a serious book, but <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Irish Boy, A Romantic Biography, The">The Irish Boy</TITLE>, be Jezus, isn&apos;t it.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 155" DBREF="68930">155</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="68616" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Strange Beginning, 1961"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1961-08-11" CERTAINTY="BY">By 11 August 1961</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PERSONAL"><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL"><PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>NJ&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Strange Beginning</TITLE> was published by <ORGNAME>Robert Hale</ORGNAME> after, to her extreme displeasure, her faithful agent <NAME>Raymond Savage</NAME> informed her that <ORGNAME>Hutchinson</ORGNAME> no longer wanted her on their list.</PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3102 (11 August 1961): 500" DBREF="54246">(11 August 1961): 500</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 181-2" DBREF="68930">181-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PERSONAL"><PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS><NAME STANDARD="Savage, Raymond">Savage</NAME> was forced to tell her, from <ORGNAME>Hutchinson</ORGNAME>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><PCIRCULATION>that her sales had slumped</PCIRCULATION> and that her mode of writing was considered out of date.</QUOTE></PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> She blamed the messenger for the news, and never forgave him. <NAME>Harold Lang</NAME> invented a fantastical tale of a revenge she was imagined playing on Hutchinson.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 182" DBREF="68930">182</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL"><PADVERTISING><ORGNAME STANDARD="Robert Hale">Hale</ORGNAME>, however, gave her flattering treatment: they announced her book at the head of their list of new titles along with another best-selling name,<NAME>Jean Plaidy</NAME>.</PADVERTISING><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3102 (11 August 1961): 500" DBREF="54246">(11 August 1961): 500</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> <PEDITIONS>The first edition was reprinted in 1973 and 1974.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Strange 1974, prelims" DBREF="68616">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT>This novel uses some familiar NJ motifs to construct its preposterous plot. <TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">It opens just after the first world war,</TSETTINGDATE> with the twenty-six-year-old former <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Paravenda, Rosie di">Rosie Power</TCHARACTERNAME>, <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE">born in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="London" REG="Walworth">Walworth</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, now the <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Paravenda, Rosie di">Contessa di Paravenda</TCHARACTERNAME> and living in <PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE>. Rosie left school at fourteen, went into <TTHEMETOPIC>musical comedy</TTHEMETOPIC>, and married a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>bookmaker</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> called <TCHARACTERNAME>Horace Barrett</TCHARACTERNAME> (who had initially hoped to get her into bed without marriage). She wonders if she has made a mistake when, soon after the wedding, he becomes violently jealous of her close friendship with a fellow <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>actor, <TCHARACTERNAME>Roddie Bernstein</TCHARACTERNAME> (whose father is a Jewish tailor)</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. When Horace takes her on holiday to the <PLACE><REGION REG="Riviera">south</REGION> of <GEOG>France</GEOG></PLACE> and then <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="gamblling">decamps to the gambling tables in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Monte Carlo</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Monaco"></GEOG></PLACE>, losing money that he hasn&apos;t got</TMOTIF>,</TSETTINGPLACE> Rosie meets and falls in love with <TCHARACTERNAME>Stefano di Paravenda</TCHARACTERNAME>, who introduces her to <TTHEMETOPIC>opera and other cultural delights</TTHEMETOPIC>, whose aged father wants him to marry for the sake of a family heir, but who is <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">impotent</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> after being badly wounded in the war.</TPLOT></P><P><TPLOT><TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="bigamy">Then Horace announces that he was married before and his marriage to Rosie is bigamous.</TMOTIF> Though his wife is now dead, he walks out on Rosie, having first extracted from her a promise to look after his eight-year-old son, another Horace Barrett, who in the long run turns out just as unpleasant as his father. Rosie, however, marries her <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>disabled beloved</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> Stefano, and adopts an Italian boy, another Stefano, who <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="inheritance">grows up into the perfect heir to the de Paravenda family estate</TMOTIF>. Rosie and Roddie remain lifelong friends but never marry, and Rosie is left living as a widow in Italy, farming, visiting, awaiting honorary grandchildren.</TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Last Novels</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="68617" PLACEHOLDER="NJ, Flavia, 1965"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1965-06-17" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid-June 1965</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY><PADVERTISING>NJ&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Flavia</TITLE> appeared posthumously, advertised as her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">last great <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>,</QUOTE> following <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Yolanda</TITLE> in 1963 and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Long Shadows</TITLE> in 1964.</PADVERTISING></PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3303 (17 June 1965): 493" DBREF="54246">(17 June 1965): 493</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Yolanda</TITLE> traces the complicated love-life of a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">woman born into a conventional, wealthy family</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, who makes her first marriage at an early age as a <TTHEMETOPIC>gesture of rebellion</TTHEMETOPIC>. When she finds life with her older husband just as conventional as that of home, she <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="adultery">embarks on an affair</TMOTIF> with a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>charming but, it proves, dislikeable man</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="divorce">He refuses to be named in a divorce case on grounds of the damage it would do his career and his family&apos;s reputation. Yolanda&apos;s <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>decent and caring husband</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> offers to simulate an affair so that she can divorce him.<SCHOLARNOTE><P>It was not until 1971, when an act passed by parliament in 1969 finally became law, that divorce could be automatically obtained after five years&apos; separation.<RESEARCHNOTE>from textbase</RESEARCHNOTE></P></SCHOLARNOTE> Yolanda declines his offer, feeling that to accept it would not be fair to him. <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="happy ending">When an old friend offers himself as co-respondent for her prospective divorce case, she first angrily supposes he is trying to lure her into an affair, then belatedly understands that he loves her, and is indeed the love of her life.</TMOTIF></TMOTIF><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Strange 1974, dustjacket back flap" DBREF="68616">dustjacket back flap</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TPLOT></P><P><TPLOT><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Long Shadows</TITLE> has another rich protagonist, Sidone, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE"><PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE> dress designer. She is unspoiled by her success</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> and makes a love-match with an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">English north-country businessman</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Strange 1974, dustjacket back" DBREF="68616">dustjacket back</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TPLOT></P><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">The action of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Flavia</TITLE> takes place in <PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="New York City">New York</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="New York"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>, and <PLACE><GEOG>Australia</GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Strange 1974, dustjacket back" DBREF="68616">dustjacket back</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGPLACE></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PATTITUDES>NJ wrote of herself: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I am not, and never shall be, a heaven-born writer, my education was too scrappy, and as I can neither punctuate nor spell correctly, that is something of a handicap.</QUOTE></PATTITUDES> <PMATERIALCONDITIONS>So was (in the early years) time devoted to her stage career, and so were her weak lungs, which she could keep functioning only by an annual visit to <PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE> and then eventually by moving there.</PMATERIALCONDITIONS> <PEARNINGS>During the 1920s while she was still acting on stage her books did not bring in much money: less than a livable income.</PEARNINGS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 215" DBREF="68825">215</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><PARCHIVALLOCATION>The <ORGNAME>Library of Congress</ORGNAME> holds a collection of her papers.</PARCHIVALLOCATION> Eleven <TGENRE GENRENAME="LETTER">letters</TGENRE> from her are included among <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Letters in <NAME>Winifred Holtby</NAME>&apos;s Collected In-mail</TITLE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ believed in omitting from books what was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">painful, coarse, and raw,</QUOTE> unless the scope of the story demanded it.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 247" DBREF="68825">247</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She prowled valiantly into an <TTHEMETOPIC>opium den in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="London" REG="Limehouse">Limehouse</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC> to investigate a <TMOTIF>murder</TMOTIF> in her rather short-lived capacity as free-lance <TGENRE GENRENAME="JOURNALISM">journalist</TGENRE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 250-1" DBREF="68825">250-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PATTITUDES>Despite having been reproved in her youth by no less a person than <NAME>Christabel Pankhurst</NAME> for her love of popularity, NJ continued to enjoy opening letters from readers.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 199-200" DBREF="68825">199-200</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL"><PCIRCULATION><NAME STANDARD="Campbell, Beatrice Stella">Mrs Patrick Campbell</NAME>, to whom she sent a copy of one of her earlier books,</PCIRCULATION> replied that she had enjoyed it, and had been <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">rather touched by your drawing of a <TTHEMETOPIC>man&apos;s faithful love</TTHEMETOPIC>!</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 236" DBREF="68825">236</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Reputation</HEADING><DIV2><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RFICTIONALIZATION>During NJ&apos;s lifetime <NAME>Harold Lang</NAME> not only guyed her in private gatherings of friends, but used her voice and mannerisms to help him interpret several stage roles.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 176-8" DBREF="68930">176-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RFICTIONALIZATION></P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN1="WRITINGCLIMATE1" RELEVANCE1="COMPREHENSIVE1"><DATE VALUE="1956-07-15">15 July 1956</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RFICTIONALIZATION><ORGNAME STANDARD="BBC" REG="British Broadcasting Corporation">BBC</ORGNAME> radio aired a play by <NAME>Harold Lang</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Tynan, Ken">Kenneth Tynan</NAME>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Quest for Corbett, The">The Quest for Corbett</TITLE>, in which NJ played the lead role as Aphra Corbett, a preposterous woman writer modelled on herself.</RFICTIONALIZATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 180-1" DBREF="68930">180-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>As a highly productive popular author, NJ has commanded almost no critical attention, although the Jewish and the lesbian aspects of her identity (both highly visible, the latter occluded for a long time for readers who had not met her) give her a unique and fascinating flavour. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Her earliest biographer, <NAME>James Norbury</NAME>, judged that she was a potential genius who squandered her talents.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 155-6" DBREF="68930">155-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He regretted the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">slipshod quality</QUOTE> of her writing, but called the Gollantz novels <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">minor masterpieces</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 156" DBREF="68930" QTDIN="QTDINYES">156</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">More recently <NAME>Paul Bailey</NAME>, stressing the antisemitic atmosphere in which these novels appeared, applauded NJ&apos;s aims but faulted her for a lack of either subtlety or wit.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 156" DBREF="68930">156</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Bailey even classed her among <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">perpetrators of fictional schlock,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 157" DBREF="68930">157</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and said that she <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">left behind an Everest of verbiage.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 183" DBREF="68930">183</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He granted to the Gollantz novels only <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">some interesting and unusual social detail.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 242" DBREF="68930">242</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Bailey, Paul. Three Queer Lives. 2001.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Bodleian Catalogue.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Furbank, P. N. Escape of a Half-Naked Sailor. 2001.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Trefusis, Violet. Don&apos;t Look Round. 1953.</SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></WRITING>